         b'L\xe2\x80\x99s <a href="http://pplv.cs.ucl.ac.uk/welcome/" target'
         b'="_top">Programming Principles, Logic and Verification Research (PPL'
         b'V) Group</a>, has been awarded the 2016 G\xc3\xb6del Prize. Peter '
         b'will receive the award jointly with Stephen Brookes, Professor of Co'
         b'mputer Science at Carnegie Mellon University, at the <a href="http:/'
         b'/www.easyconferences.eu/icalp2016/" target="_top">43rd International'
         b' Colloquium On Automata, Languages and Programming (ICALP 2016)</a>,'
         b' 12-15 July 2016, in Rome, Italy.</p>\n\n\n<p class="align-justify"'
         b'>Peter\xe2\x80\x99s paper <a href="http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm'
         b'?id=1235896.1236121" target="_top">Resources, Concurrency and Logica'
         b'l Reasoning</a> introduces and advances the idea of Concurrent Separ'
         b'ation Logic (CSL), which has had a far-reaching impact in both theor'
         b'etical and practical realms. &nbsp;</p>\n<p class="align-justify"'
         b'>For the last thirty years experts have regarded shared-memory concu'
         b'rrency as one of the greatest challenges in program verification. &n'
         b'bsp;CSL is a revolutionary advance on previous approaches. &nbsp;It '
         b'builds on the Separation Logic for sequential programs due to Peter '
         b'and the late John Reynolds, using the separation idea to support mod'
         b'ular reasoning.</p>\n<p class="align-justify">In the theoretical '
         b'realm, almost all research papers developing concurrent program logi'
         b'cs in the last decade are based on CSL, including work on permission'
         b's, refinement and atomicity, on adaptations to assembly languages an'
         b'd weak memory models, on higher-order variants, and on the logics fo'
         b'r termination of concurrent programs. </p>\n<p class="align-justi'
         b'fy">In the practical realm, the beauty of CSL is in its similarity t'
         b'o the programming idioms commonly used by working engineers. The fac'
         b't that the logic matches the common programming idioms has the effec'
         b't of greatly simplifying proofs. CSL\xe2\x80\x99s simplicity and '
         b'structure also facilitates automation. As a result, numerous tools a'
         b'nd techniques in the research community are based on it, and it is a'
         b'ttracting attention in companies such as Facebook, Microsoft, and Am'
         b'azon. </p>\n<p class="align-justify">UCL\xe2\x80\x99s PPLV Group i'
         b's further advancing the theory and application of CSL. Head of Group'
         b', Professor David Pym:</p>\n<p class="align-justify">\xe2\x80\x98C'
         b'SL is a beautiful mathematical tool that helps to solve significant '
         b'engineering problems. Scientists with the ability to deliver at the '
         b'highest level across that theory-to-application spectrum are very ra'
         b're indeed, and Peter is one of the very best. When we began work on '
         b'the underlying logical and semantic theory almost 20 years ago, the '
         b'impact that CSL would have was not merely unknown, but quite unknowa'
         b'ble. Scientists of Peter\xe2\x80\x99s stature have the insight an'
         b'd creativity to deliver beyond what can be foreseen.\xe2\x80\x99 '
         b'</p>\n<p class="align-justify">Peter has been a member of UCL'
         b'\xe2\x80\x99s PPLV Group since 2012, and is currently an Engineer'
         b'ing Manager at Facebook. He cofounded a verification start-up, Monoi'
         b'dics, which was acquired by Facebook in 2013. Peter has also held ac'
         b'ademic positions at Queen Mary University of London and at Syracuse '
         b'University.</p>\n<p class="align-justify">He is a past recipient '
         b'of a Royal Society Wolfson Research Merit Award and a Most Influenti'
         b'al POPL Paper award, and held a Royal Academy of Engineering/Microso'
         b'ft Research Chair. He obtained his BS in Computer Science from Dalho'
         b'usie University, Nova Scotia, and his MS and PhD Degrees in Computer'
         b' Science from Queen\xe2\x80\x99s University, Kingston, Canada.</p'
         b'>\n<p class="align-justify">The G\xc3\xb6del Prize is named in hono'
         b'ur of Kurt G\xc3\xb6del, who was born in Austria-Hungary (now the '
         b"Czech Republic) in 1906.&nbsp; G\xc3\xb6del's work has had immense"
         b' impact upon scientific and philosophical thinking in the 20<sup>th<'
         b'/sup> century.&nbsp; The award is presented annually by ACM\xe2'
         b'\x80\x99s <a href="http://sigact.acm.org" target="_top">Special In'
         b'terest Group on Algorithms and Computation Theory (SIGACT)</a> and t'
         b'he <a href="http://eatcs.org/" target="_top">European Association fo'
         b'r Theoretical Computer Science (EATCS)</a>.&nbsp; It recognizes majo'
         b'r contributions to mathematical logic and the foundations of compute'
         b'r science and includes an award of $5,000.</p>\r\n\t\t<div class="cl'
